    term: "Moral Object, Intention, and Circumstances",
    category: "morality",
    tags: ["fontes-moralitatis", "aquinas", "moral-analysis"],
    oneLiner: "The three sources (fontes moralitatis) that together determine the morality of any human act: what is done, why it is done, and the surrounding conditions.",
    body: "Catholic moral theology evaluates every human act through three lenses. The moral object (what is chosen) determines the act's species — whether it is by its nature ordered to or against the good. The intention (why the agent acts) can add further goodness or malice but cannot make an intrinsically evil object good. The circumstances (who, where, when, how, consequences) can increase or diminish moral responsibility but cannot transform the species of the act. All three must be good for an act to be morally good; a defect in any one renders the act evil.",
